<subSubSection id="6DE165012507FF86FF45134EFD70FD4D" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2544368A2507FF86FF45134EFD70FD4D" blockId="18.[178,1086,540,738]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">
Comment: The original description is based on &quot; 
<specimenCount id="33FDFD032507FF86FCF5134EFC33FD9D" box="[770,929,540,562]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
&quot; from &quot;Kobé&quot; (
<bibRefCitation id="416A4B7B2507FF86FF4D136BFEAEFDE0" author="SHARP D" box="[186,316,569,591]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" pagination="1 - 103" refId="ref11410" refString="SHARP D. S. (1874): The Staphylinidae of Japan. - The Transactions of the Entomological Society of London 1874: 1 - 103." type="journal article" year="1874">SHARP 1874</bibRefCitation>
). Both of them, a male and a female, were located in the collections of the BMNH. The male is designated as the 
<typeStatus id="FA4088282507FF86FDA51305FD20FDC2" box="[594,690,599,621]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">lectotype</typeStatus>
. An examination of the type material revealed that 
<taxonomicName id="E2FB4D092507FF86FEB51326FD86FD25" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1874" box="[322,532,628,650]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lathrobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kobense">
<emphasis id="178FEA982507FF86FEB51326FD86FD25" box="[322,532,628,650]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Lathrobium kobense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to 
<taxonomicName id="E2FB4D092507FF86FD621326FB9DFD25" authority="MULSANT &amp; REY 1878" authorityName="MULSANT &amp; REY" authorityYear="1878" box="[661,1039,628,650]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="178FEA982507FF86FD621326FC80FD25" box="[661,786,628,650]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Pseudobium</emphasis>
MULSANT &amp; REY 1878
</taxonomicName>
and that this species is conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="E2FB4D092507FF86FDCF13C0FCF3FD08" authority="ASSING 2012" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2012" box="[568,865,657,679]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hunanicum">
<emphasis id="178FEA982507FF86FDCF13C0FD5BFD08" box="[568,713,657,679]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">P. hunanicum</emphasis>
ASSING 2012
</taxonomicName>
, which was recently described from 
<collectingCountry id="5DEC761A2507FF86FEAF13FDFE0AFD6A" box="[344,408,687,709]" name="China" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">China</collectingCountry>
. Hence the synonymy proposed above. The external and sexual characters of the 
<typeStatus id="FA4088282507FF86FE97139EFE2FFD4D" box="[352,445,716,738]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">lectotype</typeStatus>
are illustrated in 
<figureCitation id="BDC02A0F2507FF86FD99139EFD4CFD4D" box="[622,734,716,738]" captionStart="Figs 44-47" captionStartId="18.[178,218,1466,1486]" captionTargetBox="[182,1052,816,1452]" captionTargetId="figure-300@18.[178,1085,816,1452]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 44-47: Pseudobium kobense (SHARP), lectotype: (44) habitus; (45) forebody; (46-47) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 44-45: 1.0 mm; 46-47: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303089" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303089/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Figs 44-47</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6DE165012507FF86FF4513A3FCE7FC8B" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2544368A2507FF86FF4513A3FCE7FC8B" blockId="18.[178,1085,753,804]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">
<taxonomicName id="E2FB4D092507FF86FF4513A3FE18FCA8" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2013" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[178,394,753,775]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudobium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kobense">
<emphasis id="178FEA982507FF86FF4513A3FE18FCA8" box="[178,394,753,775]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Pseudobium kobense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is now known from one locality in 
<collectingCountry id="5DEC761A2507FF86FCE313A0FCDCFCA8" box="[788,846,754,775]" name="Japan" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Japan</collectingCountry>
and three localities in 
<collectingCountry id="5DEC761A2507FF86FF45125CFF7CFC8B" box="[178,238,782,804]" name="China" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">China</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="416A4B7B2507FF86FF0B125CFE02FC8B" author="ASSING V" box="[252,400,782,804]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" pagination="409 - 419" refId="ref11020" refString="ASSING V. (2012 a): On the Pseudobium species of the Palaearctic region. III. A new species from China, a new synonymy, a new combination, and additional records (Insecta: Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 44 (1): 409 - 419." type="journal article" year="2012">ASSING 2012a</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="416A4B7B2507FF86FE6D125CFE4CFC8B" author="ASSING V" box="[410,478,782,804]" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633" pagination="229 - 245" refId="ref11256" refString="ASSING V. (2013 d): A revision of Pseudobium IV. Three new species, a new synonymy, and additional records (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 45 (1): 229 - 245." type="journal article" year="2013">2013d</bibRefCitation>
); the distribution is illustrated in 
<figureCitation id="BDC02A0F2507FF86FCDA125DFCE2FC8B" box="[813,880,782,804]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="3.[178,223,976,996]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,212,958]" captionTargetId="figure-284@3.[178,1085,212,958]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Map 1: Distributions of Lathrobium imminutum ASSING (circles), Pseudobium kobense (SHARP) (diamonds) and Lobrathium scabripenne (SHARP) (triangles) in China and Japan." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5303071" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5303071/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="1633">Map 1</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
